{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_gaston_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583978/1910110601/0076.xml":{"full_text":"wg&ggseSBBSSSArr-i y\nThomas Brigden, for many years a\nBelghbor and intimate friend of Charles\nDickens, has been a resident of Walker\ncounty for the past 38 years. He is spend\ning his last days with his sons, Just\nwaiting for the end,\u2019\u2019 he said to me a\nfew days ago when by appointment he\nmet me in the private office of Jack Cran\nford, at Jasper.\nThomas Brigden is one of the most in\nteresting characters in Alabama. He is\n77 years of age, as stout and active as\nmost men at 50. After our conversation\nBY WALTER HARPER\ntor of Ills church came by and reproved\nMr. Dickens for allowing his daughters\nto spend so much of their time romping\non the grass in the open and in view of\nthe passing public.\nDickens Was Angry\n\"Mr. Dickens said but little in reply,\nbut he plainly showed his anger. He told\nthe preacher he was one of those straight\nlaced fellows, over-pious and zealous of\nthe cause, that he could see no harm in\nchildren living close to nature and drink\ning the health and vigor of the open air.\nTHOMAS D1UGDEN\nWalker County Mnn Who for Many Years Lived an Neighbor to Great Engrllnh\nNovelist\u2014Photo by J. H. Leeres, Jasper.\nhe walked to the depot, almost a mile\nfrom Mr. Cranford's bank, caught a train\nto Carbon Hill, and after transacting his\nbusiness there walked seven miles to his\nhome in the northern part of the county.\n\"I think nothing of a walk of seven or\nten miles,\" said Mr,..Brlgden. \"I have\nnever found my limit of outdoor exercise.\nI am sure I could walk 20 miles on a\nstretch with but little fatigue. I have\nnever used tobacco In any form, use\nliquors moderately and have always led\nan active outdoor life. I feel as strong\nas I did 20 years ago.\nKnew Dickens Well\n\u201cYes, I lived neighbor to Charles Dick\nens at Gads Hill, In Kent county, Eng\nland, for a number of years. I knew him\nwell. He was a good neighbor and a good\ncompanion. People who did not know\nhim well regarded him as an irritable cad,\nihut I did not find him so. It Is true he\nwas very peculiar in his ways, hut to\nknow him well, as I did, as a neighbor,\nwas to have a high regard for his ehar\nncter. He had a most lovable disposition\nto those who came in flose and constant\ncontact with him.\n\u201cAs you know Gads Hill was the scene\ncf Prince Henry and John Falstaff's rob\nber escapes, depicted bv Shakespeare In\nbis Henry IV. At the side of the road\nleading from London to Rochester at\nCads Hill, in Dickens day, there stood an\nold Inn called the John Falstaff. Dickens\ntold me one day that this Inn first at\ntracted his attention to the place. He said\nthat on one of his drives. In his familiar\none-horse shay, he drove through Hig\nham, the village In which Gads Hill is lo\ncated. The sign over the door of the\nInn attracted his attention and he turned\nback after he had passed It a little way.\nHe made a survey of the surrounding\nscenery and liked the location, he said.\nTie later bought the place almost directly\nopposite the Inn. I later leased a place\nnot 100 yards away.\nGarden of London\n\u201cHlgham at that time was in the midst\nof what was known as the 'Garden of\nLondon.' It was surrounded by beauti\nful and fertile valley lands, which pro\nduced most of the fruits and vegetables\nused in the citv of London.\n\"Gads Hill Place, Dickens' home, was\none of the most attractive In that whole\nsection. The yard was a mass of beautiful\nflowers, mainly roses. He also bought\nt plot of ground on the opposite side of\nthe road, to which he dug a subway un\nderwrite road. This plot of ground was\nbeautifully sodded to grass and was set\nopart for a play ground for his children.\n\u201cMr. Dickens' children spent a great\ndeal of time romping on this play ground.\nI happened to' be standing on the road\nwith Mr. Dickens one day when the pas\nMORPHINE\nanrt other drug habits are aucceeafully treated by\nHABPrii&A- For hypodermic or Internal ue^ 8a\u00ab\ntole eedt 0* W <\u00bbM\u00ab l\u00bb*bltute by mall PftVV\nllcwular price M-00 per bottle at your\n4rugate* or b* null In Plain wrapper.\nDelta Chemical Co., St. Louts, Ho.\nWm Oslo hr liseta' Phumsrr. kinilnOhiu All.\nDickens did not attend church very reg\nularly, and indeed, was called an atheist\nby some people. He resented this very\nstrongly, declaring that nature itself was\nan unmistakable evidence of a divine\nhead. I heard him declare more than\nonce that \u2018Buch a wonderful machine as\nthe earth and heavens, with their regular\nity of change, could not continue to exist\nwithout an all-powerful engineer.\n\"Dickens lived ciose to the people with\nwhom be came in contact. He seemed to\nlove most to mingle with the lowest\nstrata of life. While living at Gads Hill\nhe made many excursions Into the slums\nof London. He usually employed a cousin\nof mine, a detective of Scotland Yard, to\naccompany him on these excursions. He\npaid the detective \u00a35. or *26, on each trip.\nMy cousin often told me that Dickens\nseemed to be always zealous to go to the\nvery depths of human depravity. He\nwould visit the lowest places in Iamdon\nand seemed io relish the study of the\nmeanest conditions.\n\"I asked Mr. Dickens one day about his\nInterest In this lower class, and he replied:\nMy friend Brigden, I am with these peo\nple, but I am not of them.'\nWan R Pure Man\n\"Mr. Dickens was one of the purest\nmen I ever knew. His sympathies seemed\nto be always with the poor and op\npressed.\n\"While at Gads Hill Mr. Dickens vdfci\nengaged In the publication of \u2018All the\nYear Round.' His character sketches in\ntills publication were often pictures of\npeople ho came in contact with at Gads\nHill, the John Falstaff Inn and Leather\nBottle Inn, which iatter place was about\nseven miles from his home on the road\nto Rochester. Mr. Dickens was a fre\nquent visitor at the Leather Bottle and\nseemed to like to study the characters\nthat frequented the place.\n\"He drove a one-horse shay that was\none of the familiar objects In the com\nmunity. The harness w\u2019as set with silver\nbells, the only silver bells I ever saw\nused in that way. I remember that I was\nalways careful of what I said and did in\nhis presence, fearing his caricature.\nAn Odd Pet\n\u201cWhen Dickens walked about his house\nor place he was followed by a black\nraven, as black and as ghostly as the one\nthat squawked \u2018Nevermore' in Poe\u2019s mas\nterpiece. Tills black raven was Dickens\nonly pet and it followed him with the\nfaithfulness of a dog.\n\"While at home and in his study the\ngreat author dressed in a peculiar long\nsmoking coat of some strange black ma\nterial, with long red cuffs and collar.\nMr. Dickens told me he got the idea for\nthe coat from a uniform worn by political\nprisoners in some Italian prison.\n\"Wilkie Collins, the noted novelist, was\na frequent visitor in the Dickens home.\nHe was associated with Dickens at the\ntime in\u2019the publication of \u2018All the Year\nRound.- The men and boys at Htgham\ncalled Collins \u2018The Woman In White.\u2019 He\nhad Just published his novel of this name.\nCollins, married the prettiest of the Dick\nens girls.\n\"Hans Christian Anderson was another\nnotable visitor at the Dickens home that\nI remember well. Ha came to the place\nseveral times during my residence there.\nAnderson and Dickens were close friends.\nMy Impression of Anderson was peculiar.\nHe had a strikingly child-like face, was\nsimple In manner and very retiring. I\nlooked on him with something of awe.\nKnew Duke of Wellington\n\u201cThe Duke of Wellington was another\nof the great characters that I knew. T re\nmember well his sudden death at Walmer\ncastle and the great sorrow of England\nover his demise. I saw the funeral as\nit passed down the streets of London on\nthe way to St. Paul's cathedral, where\nthe notable warrior and statesman was\nburied.\n\u201cThe Duke of Wellington, as I remem\nber him. had a most striking face and\npersonality. He was of the hull-dog\ntype. B. F. Yoakum of the Frisco rail\nroad reminds me very much of the Duke\nof Wellington in every way. I have seen\nthe little truckle bed on which the duke\ndied.\"\nMr. Brigden spends a great deal of his\ntime reading. He takes a dozen or more\nnewspapers, some of them from England,\nand Is very familiar with the world\u2019s af\nfairs.\nHe was a contractor before he came to\nAmerica in 1872. Shortly before Mr. Dick\nens died he moved away from Gads Hill\nand took a house nearer London, so as\nto be closer to his family. Most of his\ncontract work was In the city of Lon\ndon.\nComes to America\nIn 1872 he was severely Injured in a gas\nexplosion while employed in tearing down\nan old house In London. His physician\nadvised him to move to a higher and bet\nter climate and he came to America. He\nfirst stopped at Cleveland. O., but when\nwinter came on he found that the climate\nwould not suit him. He looked over the\nmeteorological charts and found that the\nrainfall in north Alabama was more even\nly distributed through the year than at\nany other point in the United States.\nJust at that time a colony of English\nmen started to Walker county to found a\nmanufacturing town. He joined them\nand has been In Walker county ever\nsince.\nHe visited Elyton a number of times\nbefore there was a Birmingham and has\nwatched the development of the Birming\nham district with considerable interest.\nSltw for Photograph\nThe photograph accompanying this ar\nticle is the first that Mr. Brigden has had\ntaken for GO years and the second that\nwas ever taken. When he sat for his\nphotograph 60 years ago he lost his chance\nto join the English volunteer forces in\nthe Crimean war, and it was with consid\nerable hesitation that he agreed to sit\nfor the picture here presented.\nHe said: \u201cWhen England called for\nvolunteers for the Crimean war T was\nthe second man to answer the call from\nthe County Kent. When I reached Lon\ndon, on the way to the recruiting office,\nI stopped at a photograph gallery to have\na picture taken for my father. This\ncaused a delay of about three hours and\nwhen I finally reached the recruiting of\nfice the lists had been closed. I swore\nthen that I would never again sit for a\nphotograph, hut if you think it will save\nthe country I will sit for you now. I am\nnot on the way to any war. I am only\nwaiting\u2014waiting for the end\u2014and have\nplenty of time on my hands.\"\nNever Reads Dickens\nWhen asked if he enjoyed reading Dick\nens\u2019 works, Mr. Brigden said:\n\u201cNo, I never read them. It would be\nsacrilege. I have heard him read and im\npersonate every one of his characters so\nwell that I am unable to get any enjoy\nment out of the dry reading of the\nbooks.\u201d\nNote\u2014For the Information of the reader\nwho may have forgotten I will add that\nCharles Dickens died at Gads Hill, In\n1870, at the age of 6R.\nThe Duke of Wellington died suddenly\nat Walmer castle in 1852.\nWilkie Collins was associated with\nDickens in his literary and publication\nwork and spent a great deal of his time at\nGads Hill.\nHans Christian Anderson, the Danish\nauthor, was born 1805 and died in 1875.\nCulinary\nFrom the Baltimore American.\n\u201cHow did that story you cooked up\nto toll your wife pan out?\"\n\u201cNaturally in a family stew.\u201d\nQUIET WEEK IN\nSTOCK MARKET\nAnticipation of Election Scare\nIs Not Realized\nBANKS ARE INFLUENTIAL\nIII Keeping speculation Well in Hounds.\nNot Strong Enough to Finance\nExtensive Campaign\non Street\nII>\u2022 ti. NICHOLAS\nNew York, November 5.\u2014(Special j\u2014This\nhas been a very quiet week In the stock\nmarket. Anticipations of an election\nscare were riot realized. The tendency\nwas so strong in orje direction, so far\nas the state of New York was concerned,\nthat there was no good chance to or\nganize a laid that amounted to anything.\nAt th<* aa^eUiroe there was a sharp fall\ning off in the volume of business and\na very general disposition to alt tight on\nI commitments already made. The gam\nbling spirit had b^en pretty well grati\nfied in bets previously made on the stock\nmarket and those who had been figur\ning on the price effect of the election\nnext Tuesday did not care to go further.\nDuring the week preceding there had\nbeen heavy profit-taking and expectations\nwere prevalent that quotations would\nreact sharply in consequence. There was\na market setback of several points buy\ntlie decline did not go anywhere near\nas far as had been commonly looked for,\nand even that small recession was made\nup in large part during the week un\ndei review. Indeed in some cases new\nhigh records were made, notably in\nCanadian Pacific, Amalgamated Copper,\nSmelters, Consolidated Gas and quite a\nnumber of the specialties.\nSteel got close up to the high point,\nand in the face of most discouraging\ntrade reports was well sustained through\nput. Not less than 150,000 shares of the\nInside long stock were unloaded during\nthe first three days of the week through\ntwo or three houses. The stuff was\ntaken without a tremor ahd at the head\nquarters of the organized bull party in\nthat issue expressions of supreme confi\ndence in a further advance alter the\nelection are disseminated.\nThis attitude is variously regarded. One\ntheory is that the bull syndicate has\nnot succeeded in unloading large lines\nbought on the way up and that it is\nunder the necessity of making a higher\nmarket if possible in order to get out\nwith the profits now\u2019 shown on paper.\nAnother theory is that this bull con\ntingent is genuinely In earnest and be\nlieves the stock to be worth a great\ndeal more than it is now selling for. Be\ntween these two theories you pay your\nmoney and you take your choice.\nThe banks played an important part\nin keeping speculation within bounds. As\npointed out in these tetters, the bank\ning situation was not strong enough at\nany time to finance a campaign that\ncalled for transactions anywhere near\n1,000,000 shares a day. 'It took several\nstrong hints for the bull leaders to get it\nthrough their heads that the banks were\nin earnest in advising a drawing in of\nhorns, yet when the truth was driven in\nhard enough enthusiasm was subdued\nand the boom subsided measurably. It\nwas a knowledge that this action would\nhave to take place that induced the be\nlief in an important reaction.\nThe underlying strength of sentiment\nproved, however, to be much greater titan\nbad. been appraised and we see the pleas\nant and somewhat surprising fact of a\nsubstantial undertone extending beyond\nanticipated limits of time.\nSpeculative attention is now being\ngiven to the problem of \"what will hap\npen after the election?\" There is a wide\ndivergence of opinion on this interesting\nissue. The surface idea is that in the\nevent of an overwhelming rebuke of po\nlitical radicalism in this state the gener\nal public will enjoy a complete restora\ntion of confidence which will be followed\nhv a resumption of business activity in\nevery direction.\nIt is upon this theory that a large\npart of the investment buying of the last\nthree or four weeks has been predicated.\nA fear grows up, however, that no mat\nter how impressive the election in this\npart of the country may be, the voting in\nthe west and south will have a different\nslant and results be open to a different\nconstruction. The thought obtrudes\ncontinually that no matter wiiat hap\npens the country is very likely to have\ntwo or three years of very sensational\npolitical agitation.\nWith progressives and democrats in\ncontrol of one or both branches of Con\ngress, as now' seems to be entirely prob\nable, there can be no escape from dis\ntal bing action along several distinctive\nlines_tariff revision, clamor for more\nstrongly defined regulation of railroads\nand other corporations, prolongation of\nthe- fight over freight rates, all of this\nsupplemented by a flood of investiga\ntions covering an infinite variety of sub\njects ranging from the Panama canal\ndown to and including extravagance in\ngovernmental expenditures, political con\ntributions by undesirable rich and every\nphase of the high and increasing cost of\nliving. That this line of /igitation can\nproceed to the lengths that are threat\nened without disturbing values and fur\nther checking the return of prosperity,\ncannot be hoped for.\nPeople who- take this view of the fu\nture arc not optimistic on the stock mar\nket. On the contrary they believe that\nthe trend of prices will he downward for\ntwo or three years and that we are in\nfor that long a period of hard times with\nall attendant embarrassments and pri\nvation.\nActual news developments this week\nhave not been of highest importance.\nThe publicity man of the Steel corpora\ntion came out with another one of his\nfamous \"canned\" interviews picturing the\ncondition of tlie iron trade as being lum\ninously bright, although advices from the\nmilling centers are directly in contradic\ntion of these inspired expressions.\nA particularly impressive part of this\ninterview was the holy announcement\nthat the Steel corporation management\nwas engaged In the manufacturing busi\nness and was paying no attention to mar\nket manipulation or the fluctuations in\nthe prices of stocks. Tills sort of thing\nmav be swallowed by an innocent pub\nlic, but It certainly raised a laugh In Wall\nstreet, where everybody knows that the\nSteel corporation management Includes\nseveral of the most active market plung\ners in America, men who are notorious\nas being desperate gamblers, and who\nspecialize on Steel.\nHowever, if that rfort of output Is the\ntonic required, the premier publicity\nagent of the corporation is equal to any\ndemand that may he imposed upon him\nin this respect. He is certainly a star\nperformer in handing out the dope. As a\nmixer of good medicine he has no equal.\nThe trouble Is fewer people take it than\nformerly. It has begun to pall on the\ntaste. Speaking of the Steel corporation,\np is expected tlmt the statement of ton\nnage on the books, due In two or three\ndays, is expected to.be very discourag\ning. and the public mind has been pre\npared for the bad showing.\nEverybody is glad the political cam\npaign Is drawing to a close. There is\nnot much chance fof traders to get a\ncomprehensive line on the market until\nafter the ballots are counted and a lit\ntle time given to estimate effects and con\nsequences.\nThe price changes of late are little\nmore I ban a reflection of the betting\nodds on the election of Mr. Dix to be\nHeaters, Steel Ranges and Dinner Sets\nWe Are Making Special Prices On Heating Stoves; We Are\nMaking Reduced Prices On Dinner Sets and All Other Crockery\nSpecial Reduced Prices On Coal Hods, Fire Screens, Shovels, Pokers, Fire Sets\nand All Other Winter Goods.\nPENINSULA\nA Special Peninsular\nRange at $25\nWorth $40.00 Regularly\nHere Is a chance to buy a\nstrictly high-grade Steel Range\nat a mighty small price. This\nPeninsular Steel Range is made\nwith large fire box and double\nasbestos lined oven. You know\nthere are no ranges superior to\nthe famous Peninsular. The> arc\nused in hundreds of the best\nhomes in this city. Why not have\none in your home\"\nSpecial\n$35 Haviland Dinner\nSet $24.95\n100-piece Haviland\nChina Dinner Sets. Sev\neral beautiful new de\ncorations and shapes to\nchoose from, arid every\npiece in the set the most\nuseful. These sets sell\nregularly for $35.00,\nand are considered\ncheap at that price\nNow Specially Priced\nAt $24.95\nFrench China Dinner\nSets, worth $50.00,\nal $38.95\nBeautiful English\nPorcelain Dinner\nSets, at. .$6.95 to $35\nIf You Want Toys\nCome to our big store.\nOur Toy Stocks are now\ncomplete <jnd whatever\nyou desire in the way\nof a toy will be found\nhere at a little price.\nThe Fair\n2020 2d Ave.\n2021 3d Ave.\nThe Best Heaters Are\nAlways Cheapest\nThe Heaters we /ell\u2014-THE PEN\nINSULAR\u2014have been thoroughly\ntested and have always given satis\nfaction to those who have used\nthem. We have all styles \u2018and all\nprices, and our best heaters will not\ncost you as much as other houses\nwill charge for the cheaper sorts. j\nPrices $2.95 to $50.00\ngovernor of New York. As the odds\nlengthened, prices advanced and the ebbs\nand (lows In the odds formed a basis for\noperations on the stock exchange. For\nthe moment other considerations had to\ntake a back seat.\nLater on the fundamentals will get\nback into the forefront. As someone\npertinently remarked, there is nnjre vlr\ntrue In a 19,000,000 crop than in tile suc\ncess of any political party or the de\nfeat of any of the newtsms which may\nbe advanced by the apostles of so-called\nprogressive creeds and deviations from\nthe straight line of sane and sober proce\ndure.\nRailway earnings are not coining In as\nowners would like to see. Comparisons\nwith thes piendld records of last year are\nunfavorable. Last year's gross was a\nrecord-hreaker and although there was a\ntremendous increase in operating ex\npenses net results held up remarkably\nwell.\nThe returns that are coming in nowr\nshow a decrease in gross and also a fall\ning off in cost of carrying on the busi\nness. Railroads are practicing economies\nin many directions, although it would\nappear that they are spending a lot of\nmoney in maintenance and that sort of\nthing which might also be saved without\nserious detriment to plant. This Is giv\ning shippers a good peg to hang the\ncharge and argument that the railroads\nare spending money in cider to influence\nthe interstate commerce commission In\nthe great light for and against an ad\nvance in freight rates.\nThere is just enough to this charge to\nmake it effective. The inference from\ntills condition of affairs Is that the rail\nroads are giving themselves a shade the\nbest of it in the matter of bookkeeping\nand that the transportation companies are\nin reality in better shape than they try\nto make It appear.\nThe activity and strength in Amalga\nmated Copper and Smelters was largely\nllie result of manipulation. Smelters .has\nbeen able to put through a piece of\nfinancing based on its ability to borrow\n$15,000,0011 to pay off back debts and to\nadd to Its working capital. Enemies of\nthe Smelting company are cruel enough\nto say that a part of the money thus\nborrowed will in some indirect way make\ngood the payment of dividends, an allega\ntion which is being violently denied\nfrom headquarters.\nThe background of the copper share\nstrength is a supposed Improvement In\nthe copper metal situation. This improve\nment is one point real and about five\npoints artificial. The manipulation Is\nwell handled and tips that have gone out\nare being made good. Eventually the\nprogramme will probably land the pub\nlic with a mass of copper and smelter\nstocks at high prices.\nNovember disbursements of all sorts for\ncorporation dividends and interest will\napproximate $120,000,000. instead of around\n$1111,000,000, ns the statistics first figured.\nVerbal Play\nFrom the Chicago News.\nEmployee\u2014f am totally played out.\nEmployer\u2014I knew It was only a mat\nter of time until you would be.\nEmployee\u2014Why do you say that?\nEmployer\u2014Because I knew you could\nnot possibly work yourself out.\nDR. ELKOURIE DEFENDS CLUB\nThinks Man Who Made Such Attack As That of J. 0. Thomp\nson Is Unworthy to Be Governor\nof Alabama\nl Communicated\nIf there were no other reasons for\nwhich all of the democrats of Alabama\nshould vole against Joseph O. Thompson\nthan that of the malicious insinuations\nast upon the membership of the Young\nMen\u2019s Good Government club, in his\nstatement, which is herein reprinted:\n\u201cNothing could more aptly illustrate\nthat for which he stands than that, In Ills\nclosing speech here, he should address a\nclub organized solely for the express pur\npose of defeating the efforts of the moral,\nlaw-abiding people of this community to\nsuppress the sale of intoxicating liquors\nin this state. Before such a club Emmet\nO'Neal appears with appropirate com\npany to encourage that club In the work\nfor which it was organized and is main\ntained.\"\nThis one reason is amply sufficient to\nshow manifestly what character of man\nis asking for the dignified office of gov\nernor of tlie state of Alabama.\nAny man who is so narrow and so bi\ngoted as to caat suspicions and insinua\ntlona on a body of citizen* because they\ndared to declare and support a/principle\nthey advocated and believed in is too\nnarrow to be entrusted with the chief\nexecutiveship of a great state like Ala\nbama.\nITls statement to the effect that the club\nwas organized and is maintained to de\nfeat the efforts of the moral, law-abiding\npeople to suppress the sale of intoxicant\nliquor Is absolutely without foundation.\nThe membership of the club Is com\nposed of moral and law-abiding men, ami\nwo defy Mr. Thompson to prove the con\ntrary.\nThe club has the privilege of declaring\nfor and supporting any principle or can\ndidate that \\frill further the interest of\ngood government and promote the welfare\nof the common people, to which class\nhave the honor to belong, and in whom\nam proud and sincerely believe that they\nare the best people on earth in moral3,\ngood citizenship and loyalty.\nDR. 1-1. A. ELKOI'RIK.\nNovember 13, 1910.\nWEDS SISTER OF\nDIVORCED WIFE\nNew York. November 5.\u2014With the\nhearty approval of his divorced wife,\nSeymour L. Locke married his sister-in\nlaw, Miss Margaret G. Greenleas, a\nmagazine writer, whose home is in Lex\nington, Ky. The first Mrs. Locke was so\nfar from bearmg enmity toward her sis\nter that it was at her request that her\nson was his father\u2019s best man at the cere\nmony.\nThe newly marired couple are at pres\nent at Coleman Falls, Va., on their\nhoneymoon. Although they were married\nseveral weeks ago, cards announcing the\nmarriage were not received here until to\nday. The first Mrs. Locke obtained her\ndivorce in Los Angeles, Cal., in 1909 and\nwas granted a small portion of her hus\nband\u2019s property located at Pasadena, Cal.\nShe then returned to New York, whore\nshe now resides.\nWhen asked to comment on the mar\nriage sho said:\n\"Ho should have married Margaret in\nthe first place. I was quite willing he\nshould marry her now.\"\nFour Taste Uunlltlcs\nFrom the Chicago Tribune.\nOnly four distinct taste qualities are\ndiscoverable by the human tongue is\nthe announcement of a scientist. Sweets\nand suits, two of the taste qualities, are\nobservable at the tip of the tongue, and\nIn determining whether the white crys\ntals be salt or sweet the iIp of the\ntongue unconsciously is used. Sour and\nbitter flavors are the other strictly\ntongue tastes anti can be determined only\nupon being carried back upon the tongue\ntoward its root, when the sensations will\nbe interpreted to the brain by tlie edges\nof that organ. Dry substances that re\nmain dry cannot be tasted, and many\nthings remain tasteless to us. not because\nthey are tasteless, but because they are\nnot soluble In water. Again, spices are\ndifferentiated through the correlative\nsense of smell. Holding the nose and\nchewing a raw onion and a raw apple by\nturns, the gustatory nerves will show\nlittle or no difference in the flavor of the\ntwo.\nSo Trouble to Show floods\n\u201cThis necklace, madam.'' said the\nsalesman newly promoted to the curio\ndepartment, \u201cwas originally made for\nthe Duke of Buckingham, who gave it\nto Anne of Austria. We\u2019re selling a lot\nof them.\u201d\nBicycle stolen from Age-Her\nald building; black frame Vic\ntor, Morrow coaster; $5 reward\nfor information leading to re\ncovery. Bell phone 4900.\nhot drinks at our FOUNTAIN\nI Again We |_i V Six Cakes\nI Say, r M. Palmolive Soap I\n\nWith One Jar\nPalmolive Cream\nHaving received a fresh supply of Palmolive Soap\nand Cream, we are prepared to redeem your Coupon\non this basis.\nAdams Drug Company\n1001 The Sleepless Store in the Heart of the Town\u2019s Heart 1001\nPhones Second and Nineteenth Phones\ni \u25a0.j-'fy'. --jffiSKffi?!!","height":"28028","width":"19596"}}
